<subSubSection id="3AD53BCCFFB1FF9CFF6683C16AEDBCC7" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" type="description">
<paragraph id="72706847FFB1FF9CFF6683C1689ABD2F" blockId="16.[151,1437,565,1971]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFF6683C16B79BABF" bold="true" box="[199,365,939,964]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Description. (</emphasis>
based on material from Northeastern 
<collectingCountry id="0AD828D7FFB1FF9CFC8583C1697CBABF" box="[804,872,939,964]" name="Brazil" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Brazil</collectingCountry>
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFCC983C16965BABF" bold="true" box="[872,881,939,964]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">)</emphasis>
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFCDD83C16E00BABF" box="[892,1044,939,964]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Gnathopod 1</emphasis>
coxa 1 with anteroventral corner acute and slightly produced, basis longer than ischium and merus together; carpus elongated with discreet anterodistal excavation, ventral margin with dense row of plumose setae; propodus subequal in length to carpus, posterior margin with 3 sets of simple setae, palm beset with minute setae; dactylar inner margin with slight sinuosity, not clear in all specimens (
<figureCitation id="EAF474C2FFB1FF9CFD9284516894BD2F" box="[563,640,1083,1108]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1966,1988]" captionTargetBox="[170,1425,392,1898]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[150,1436,372,1915]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 15. Quadrimaera pieteri Krapp Schickel &amp; Ruffo, 2000: male 4.0 mm. Marine State Park of Pedra da Risca do Meio (3 o 33’ 800”S, 38 o 26’ 000” W), Ceará state, Brazil. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (Gn1, Gn2, P5, P7); 0.3 mm (U2, U3, T)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615713/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Fig 15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="72706847FFB1FF9CFF66843569C9BC73" blockId="16.[151,1437,565,1971]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFF6684356B4FBD0C" box="[199,347,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Gnathopod 2</emphasis>
, coxa 2 subquadrate, beset with small setae; basis strong, posterior margin with 2 slender setae; carpus reduced, subtriangular; propodus enlarged, propodus palm ornamented with clear central U-shaped excavation, preceded by proximal subtriangular process and proceeded by distal subrectangular process, palm defined by an acute process strongly to weakly pronounced, preceded by U to V-shaped excavation; dactyl inner margin with weakly to strong sinuosity, visible in both specimens (
<figureCitation id="EAF474C2FFB1FF9CFC22848569C4BC73" box="[899,976,1263,1288]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1966,1988]" captionTargetBox="[170,1425,392,1898]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[150,1436,372,1915]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 15. Quadrimaera pieteri Krapp Schickel &amp; Ruffo, 2000: male 4.0 mm. Marine State Park of Pedra da Risca do Meio (3 o 33’ 800”S, 38 o 26’ 000” W), Ceará state, Brazil. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (Gn1, Gn2, P5, P7); 0.3 mm (U2, U3, T)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615713/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Fig 15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="72706847FFB1FF9CFF6685796AEDBCC7" blockId="16.[151,1437,565,1971]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFF6685796B5CBC50" box="[199,328,1299,1324]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Pereopod 5</emphasis>
with slender basis, posteroventral corner rounded and produced, dactyl with a bifid nail. 
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFA9185796AB1BC34" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Pereopod 7</emphasis>
basis with posterior margin strongly globose; propodus posterior margin with long setae. 
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFB1F855D6F38BC34" box="[1214,1324,1335,1360]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Uropod 2</emphasis>
peduncle slightly longer than rami; outer and inner rami similar in length. 
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFCCA853169C2BC0F" box="[875,982,1371,1396]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Uropod 3</emphasis>
peduncle shorter than rami, outer ramus longer than inner, with 2 sets of setae. 
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFDEC85156887BCE3" box="[589,659,1407,1432]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Telson</emphasis>
deeply cleft, telson lobes with 3 distal setae as long as telson length (
<figureCitation id="EAF474C2FFB1FF9CFF3E85C96AFFBCC7" box="[159,235,1443,1468]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1966,1988]" captionTargetBox="[170,1425,392,1898]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[150,1436,372,1915]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 15. Quadrimaera pieteri Krapp Schickel &amp; Ruffo, 2000: male 4.0 mm. Marine State Park of Pedra da Risca do Meio (3 o 33’ 800”S, 38 o 26’ 000” W), Ceará state, Brazil. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (Gn1, Gn2, P5, P7); 0.3 mm (U2, U3, T)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615713/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Fig 15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3AD53BCCFFB1FF9CFF6685AD6B1DBEC8" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="72706847FFB1FF9CFF6685AD6B1DBEC8" blockId="16.[151,1437,565,1971]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFF6685AD6B2FBC9B" bold="true" box="[199,315,1479,1504]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Remarks.</emphasis>
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF13C4FFB1FF9CFE5985AD68FDBCA4" authorityName="Krapp-Schickel &amp; Ruffo" authorityYear="2000" box="[504,745,1479,1504]" class="Malacostraca" family="Melitidae" genus="Quadrimaera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pieteri">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFE5985AD68FDBCA4" box="[504,745,1479,1504]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Quadrimaera pieteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described from the northeastern 
<collectingCountry id="0AD828D7FFB1FF9CFB2385AD6EDDBC9B" box="[1154,1225,1479,1504]" name="Brazil" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, differs from the 
<typeStatus id="AD74D6E5FFB1FF9CFF3685866B16BF7F" box="[151,258,1516,1540]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">paratypes</typeStatus>
from Lesser Islands because of the posterior margin of P7 that is slightly more globose than the specimens from the type locality (this difference is not clearly observed in females), and by having U2 with peduncle longer than rami while the 
<typeStatus id="AD74D6E5FFB1FF9CFD9D865E68B3BF37" box="[572,679,1588,1612]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">paratypes</typeStatus>
examined have a similar length. Considering that these characters are sexually dimorphic in many genera of Family 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF13C4FFB1FF9CFD73863D692BBF0B" authorityName="Krapp-Schickel" authorityYear="2009" box="[722,831,1623,1648]" class="Malacostraca" family="Maeridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Maeridae</taxonomicName>
, including 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF13C4FFB1FF9CFC1C863D6E41BF0B" authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1852" box="[957,1109,1623,1648]" class="Malacostraca" family="Melitidae" genus="Quadrimaera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFC1C863D6E41BF0B" box="[957,1109,1623,1648]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Quadrimaera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the original description of 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF13C4FFB1FF9CFF1B86166B3DBFE8" authorityName="Krapp-Schickel &amp; Ruffo" authorityYear="2000" box="[186,297,1660,1683]" class="Malacostraca" family="Melitidae" genus="Quadrimaera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pieteri">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFF1B86166B3DBFE8" box="[186,297,1660,1683]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Q. pieteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was based in an ovigerous female, we consider that the specimens here analyzed belong to this species. These specimens are also very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF13C4FFB1FF9CFD6886F56975BFC3" authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1852" box="[713,865,1695,1720]" class="Malacostraca" family="Melitidae" genus="Quadrimaera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFD6886F56975BFC3" box="[713,865,1695,1720]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Quadrimaera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
prope 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF13C4FFB1FF9CFC1186CA6F4ABFCC" authority="Krapp-Schickel &amp; Ruffo, 2000" authorityName="Krapp-Schickel &amp; Ruffo" authorityYear="2000" box="[944,1374,1695,1720]" class="Malacostraca" family="Melitidae" genus="Quadrimaera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pieteri">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFC1186CA69EDBFCC" box="[944,1017,1696,1719]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">pieteri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="165E15B6FFB1FF9CFBA086F56F4ABFCC" author="Krapp-Schickel, T. &amp; Ruffo, S." box="[1025,1374,1695,1720]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" pagination="193 - 214" refId="ref12830" refString="Krapp-Schickel, T. &amp; Ruffo, S. (2000) The Maera quadrimana - complex (Crustacea Amphipoda, Melitidae) demands a new concept: Quadrimaera n. gen. (with description of three new species from Western Atlantic). Bollettino del Museo Civicodi Storia Naturale di Ferona, 24, 193 - 214." type="journal article" year="2000">Krapp-Schickel &amp; Ruffo, 2000</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion id="B00BA6A5FFB1FF9CFF3686A96B54BFA7" box="[151,320,1731,1756]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
, especially by the palm variations of gnathopod 2 propodus and the sets of setae of the U3 outer ramus. The genus 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF13C4FFB1FF9CFEC9868D6815BE7B" authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1852" box="[360,513,1767,1792]" class="Malacostraca" family="Melitidae" genus="Quadrimaera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFEC9868D6815BE7B" box="[360,513,1767,1792]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Quadrimaera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known to present variations on Gnathopod 2 propodus palm between females, ovigerous females, juveniles, adult and hyperadult males. Moreover, 
<bibRefCitation id="165E15B6FFB1FF9CFC0987666E95BE5F" author="Krapp, T. &amp; Marti, A. &amp; Ruffo, S." box="[936,1153,1803,1828]" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" pagination="27 - 51" refId="ref12784" refString="Krapp, T., Marti, A. &amp; Ruffo, S. (1996) Three new Mediterranean Maera with remarks on the Quadrimana complex (Crustacea, Amphipoda, Melitidae). Beaufortia, 46 (3), 27 - 51." type="journal article" year="1996">Krapp et al. (1996)</bibRefCitation>
reported the presence of intermediate, and hybrid species, resulting from the reproduction between different species of the Pacific 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF13C4FFB1FF9CFF3687396B3BBE17" authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1852" box="[151,303,1875,1900]" class="Malacostraca" family="Melitidae" genus="Quadrimaera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFF3687396B3BBE17" box="[151,303,1875,1900]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Quadrimaera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Thus, considering the variations founded among Brazilian and Caribbean specimens, and the wide intraspecific polymorphism of 
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFE55871D686ABEEB" box="[500,638,1911,1936]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Quadrimera</emphasis>
, it is assumed that all Brazilian specimens belong to the same species 
<taxonomicName id="B5CF13C4FFB1FF9CFF3687F66B16BEC8" authorityName="Krapp-Schickel &amp; Ruffo" authorityYear="2000" box="[151,258,1948,1971]" class="Malacostraca" family="Melitidae" genus="Quadrimaera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pieteri">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB1FF9CFF3687F66B16BEC8" box="[151,258,1948,1971]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="583">Q. pieteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3AD53BCCFFB0FF9DFF6680FD6F66B867" pageId="17" pageNumber="584" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="72706847FFB0FF9DFF6680FD6F66B867" blockId="17.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="17" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB0FF9DFF6680FD6B74B9CB" bold="true" box="[199,352,151,176]" pageId="17" pageNumber="584">Distribution.</emphasis>
Lesser Antilles, Caribbean Sea (
<typeStatus id="AD74D6E5FFB0FF9DFD7D80F26901B9CB" box="[732,789,152,176]" pageId="17" pageNumber="584">Type</typeStatus>
locality). In 
<collectingCountry id="0AD828D7FFB0FF9DFC0F80FD69E1B9CB" box="[942,1013,151,176]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="584">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, Parque Nacional Pedra da Risca do Meio, 
<collectingRegion id="B00BA6A5FFB0FF9DFF4080D66B36B9AF" box="[225,290,188,212]" country="Brazil" name="Ceara" pageId="17" pageNumber="584">Ceará</collectingRegion>
State. Pirangi beach, 
<collectingRegion id="B00BA6A5FFB0FF9DFDBA80D6691EB9AF" box="[539,778,188,213]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Norte" pageId="17" pageNumber="584">Rio Grande do Norte</collectingRegion>
State. Boipeba beach, 
<collectingRegion id="B00BA6A5FFB0FF9DFBAE80D66E44B9AE" box="[1039,1104,188,213]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="17" pageNumber="584">Bahia</collectingRegion>
State. Prainha beach, Arraial do Cabo, 
<collectingRegion id="B00BA6A5FFB0FF9DFEA280B56BB0B983" box="[259,420,223,248]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="17" pageNumber="584">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
State. The species shows a continuous distribution from the Caribbean Sea to southeastern Brazilian coast, being restricted to the Tropical Atlantic Marine Eco region proposed by 
<bibRefCitation id="165E15B6FFB0FF9DFBD7816E6F79B867" author="Spalding M. D. &amp; Fox, H. E. &amp; Allen, G. R. &amp; Davidson, N. &amp; Ferdana, Z. A. &amp; Finlayson, M. &amp; Halpern, B. S. &amp; Jorge, M. A. &amp; Lombana, A. &amp; Lourie, S. A. &amp; Martin, K. D. &amp; McManus, E. &amp; Molnar, J. &amp; Recchia, C. A. &amp; Robertson, J." box="[1142,1389,260,285]" pageId="17" pageNumber="584" pagination="573 - 583" refId="ref13295" refString="Spalding M. D., Fox, H. E., Allen, G. R., Davidson, N., Ferdana, Z. A., Finlayson, M., Halpern, B. S., Jorge, M. A., Lombana, A., Lourie, S. A., Martin, K. D., McManus, E., Molnar, J., Recchia, C. A. &amp; Robertson, J. (2007) Marine ecoregions of the world: a bioregionalization of coastal and shelf areas. BioScience, 57, 573 - 583. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1641 / b 570707" type="journal article" year="2007">
Spalding 
<emphasis id="40BBB455FFB0FF9DFB41816F6F0DB866" box="[1248,1305,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="584">et al.</emphasis>
(2007)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
